amarantin installation
======================

This project is expected to build in two environments.

The first is on the uBooNE GPVMs using the provided .container.sh and .setup.sh
scripts.

The second is in the Docker-based portable development container.

Dependencies
------------

Required
  CMake 3.16 or newer
  C++17 compiler
  ROOT
  SQLite3 development files

Optional
  nlohmann_json headers, only if needed by your local build

GPVM and Fermilab container workflow
------------------------------------

The intended native environment is the Fermilab stack. The repository includes
.container.sh and .setup.sh.

Typical usage on a GPVM is:

    source ./.container.sh

This drops you into the expected container environment. Inside that
environment, run:

    source ./.setup.sh

Then configure and build from the repository root:

    cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
    cmake --build build --parallel

If you want to install into a local prefix:

    cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX=$PWD/install
    cmake --build build --parallel
    cmake --install build

Portable Docker workflow
------------------------

Build the development image from the repository root:

    docker build -t amarantin-dev .

Run the repository inside the container:

    docker run --rm -it -v "$PWD":/work -w /work amarantin-dev

Then configure and build:

    cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
    cmake --build build --parallel

One-shot build without opening a shell:

    docker run --rm -v "$PWD":/work -w /work amarantin-dev \
      cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release

    docker run --rm -v "$PWD":/work -w /work amarantin-dev \
      cmake --build build --parallel

Configuration notes
-------------------

Use an out-of-source build:

    cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release
    cmake --build build --parallel

To build only the library and skip mk_sample:

    cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release -DAMARANTIN_BUILD_APP=OFF

ROOT is located in one of two ways.

If ROOT_DIR is set, CMake uses the ROOT CMake package.

Otherwise, if root-config is on PATH, the build uses root-config directly.

If ROOT is not discovered automatically and you have a working ROOT CMake
package, run:

    cmake -S . -B build -DROOT_DIR=/path/to/directory/containing/ROOTConfig.cmake

If nlohmann_json headers are needed but no CMake package is available, run:

    cmake -S . -B build -DNLOHMANN_JSON_INC=/path/to/include

Install
-------

Install from an existing build tree:

    cmake --install build

Installed files
---------------

    ${prefix}/lib/libIO.so
    ${prefix}/bin/mk_sample
    ${prefix}/include/amarantin/*.hh
    ${prefix}/lib/cmake/amarantin/amarantinConfig.cmake

Downstream CMake use
--------------------

    find_package(amarantin CONFIG REQUIRED)
    target_link_libraries(your_target PRIVATE amarantin::IO)

Notes
-----

Running mk_sample with no arguments prints its usage string.

SampleIO uses the beam database in one of two ways.

If AMARANTIN_RUN_DB is set, that path is used.

Otherwise it falls back to /exp/uboone/data/uboonebeam/beamdb/run.db.

The Docker image currently uses an amd64 ROOT base image. On arm64 hosts,
Docker may build and run it under emulation.
